00:02:00.050 --> 00:02:01.400
It is actually pretty simple.

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:03.920
But algebraically
complicated, or I

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:07.070
should say trigonometrically,
very complicated.

00:02:07.070 --> 00:02:09.860
So because we don't want
to deal with that stuff.

00:02:09.860 --> 00:02:13.220
And it also hides a
lot of the intuition,

00:02:13.220 --> 00:02:16.640
we derived this paraxial
approximation which

00:02:16.640 --> 00:02:19.820
is true for a pretty limited--

00:02:19.820 --> 00:02:23.900
typically 10 to 30 degrees.

00:02:23.900 --> 00:02:27.440
Actually 30 is too optimistic,
maybe 10 to 20 degrees

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:29.870
from the optical axis.

00:02:29.870 --> 00:02:32.540
We discovered that there
is a linear relationship

00:02:32.540 --> 00:02:40.900
between them, elevation and
angle of a ray that is arriving

00:02:40.900 --> 00:02:43.540
from the left to the interface.

00:02:43.540 --> 00:02:48.010
And the elevation and angle
of propagation of array

00:02:48.010 --> 00:02:52.430
that is departing to the
right over the interface,

00:02:52.430 --> 00:02:54.130
the same rate, that
is [INAUDIBLE]..

00:02:54.130 --> 00:02:57.370
And of course, the elevation
is the same because

00:02:57.370 --> 00:02:59.590
of the paraxial
approximation, we

00:02:59.590 --> 00:03:02.650
neglect the thickness
of the instrument.

00:03:02.650 --> 00:03:05.890
So basically, no matter where
the ray hits, here or here

00:03:05.890 --> 00:03:08.020
or here, it is all the same.

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:09.850
So that helps.

00:03:09.850 --> 00:03:15.070
And the second is that the
angle, basically the angle

00:03:15.070 --> 00:03:18.160
satisfies Snell's
law with respect

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:22.180
to the normal at this sphere
at this location over here.

00:03:22.180 --> 00:03:24.070
But of course, because
this orientation

00:03:24.070 --> 00:03:29.640
depends on the relative position
of the arrival of the ray

00:03:29.640 --> 00:03:32.650
and the center of
the sphere, then we

00:03:32.650 --> 00:03:37.940
simplified it using the
paraxial approximations.

00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:40.970
And we discovered this
expression over here.

00:03:40.970 --> 00:03:44.680
So the relationship between
the right and the left angle,

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:48.370
it has to do with the elevation.

00:03:48.370 --> 00:03:50.440
So if you look at
this equation, it

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:55.360
says that n-right, alpha-right
equals n-left alpha-left.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:56.800
That's the first term.

00:03:56.800 --> 00:03:59.350
And then the interesting part
is the second one that says

00:03:59.350 --> 00:04:04.660
equals minus this quantity
times the elevation of the ray.

00:04:04.660 --> 00:04:06.940
So that tells you
that the more--

00:04:06.940 --> 00:04:12.830
the higher the arrival elevation
of the ray, the more it bends.

00:04:12.830 --> 00:04:15.460
And that makes sense because
the higher the arrival,

00:04:15.460 --> 00:04:18.850
the larger the angle that
it makes with respect

00:04:18.850 --> 00:04:23.920
to the normal to the sphere
and, therefore, if you wish,

00:04:23.920 --> 00:04:26.890
the more violent the
Snell's law will be.

00:04:26.890 --> 00:04:29.890
And of course, you can imagine,
as you increase the angle,

00:04:29.890 --> 00:04:33.220
eventually the angle
becomes so large

00:04:33.220 --> 00:04:35.250
that the paraxial
approximation breaks down.

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:37.570
But this is all true.

00:04:37.570 --> 00:04:39.535
Before the approximation
breaks down,

00:04:39.535 --> 00:04:41.950
the progression is linear.

00:04:41.950 --> 00:04:44.730
It is linear in the position.

00:04:44.730 --> 00:04:48.090
And the quantity that appears
here, does anybody remember?

00:04:48.090 --> 00:04:49.340
