Yes, I did.

00:59:46.490 --> 00:59:46.990
Didn't I?

00:59:46.990 --> 00:59:47.380
Yay.

00:59:47.380 --> 00:59:48.255
I'm sorry about that.

00:59:51.492 --> 00:59:53.440
I think I better do this over.

01:00:10.170 --> 01:00:12.010
So this is s for the parabola.

01:00:12.010 --> 01:00:13.670
This is s for the sphere.

01:00:17.120 --> 01:00:29.050
So of course it would be s
plus R squared plus x squared

01:00:29.050 --> 01:00:31.240
equals R squared.

01:00:31.240 --> 01:00:37.760
So that means that s equals
minus R plus minus square root

01:00:37.760 --> 01:00:41.440
R squared minus x squared.

01:00:41.440 --> 01:00:44.860
Now which signs would I
keep, the plus or the minus?

01:00:44.860 --> 01:00:49.610
Well, the minus sign, you can
see a little bit by inspection,

01:00:49.610 --> 01:00:53.060
the minus sign is this
part of the sphere which

01:00:53.060 --> 01:00:57.260
is pretty far from the paraxial
approximation, clearly, right?

01:00:57.260 --> 01:00:59.660
So the only way to deal with
a paraxial approximation

01:00:59.660 --> 01:01:01.400
is to keep the plus sign.

01:01:01.400 --> 01:01:06.440
So we'll write, then, s equals
minus R plus the next step you

01:01:06.440 --> 01:01:09.300
do to derive paraxial
approximations

01:01:09.300 --> 01:01:13.500
is you pull a large quantity
out of the square root.

01:01:13.500 --> 01:01:15.365
So the large quantities,
the radius here,

01:01:15.365 --> 01:01:16.490
and you write it like this.

01:01:16.490 --> 01:01:20.330
1 minus x squared
over R squared.

01:01:20.330 --> 01:01:23.880
Then you apply a Taylor formula
that says that square root of 1

01:01:23.880 --> 01:01:31.250
plus small approximately equals
1 plus the small divided by 2.

01:01:31.250 --> 01:01:32.870
And note, of course,
that applies also

01:01:32.870 --> 01:01:34.790
for a negative sign.

01:01:34.790 --> 01:01:38.210
So I can do like this.

01:01:38.210 --> 01:01:44.600
And this means that s equals
minus R plus R 1 minus x

01:01:44.600 --> 01:01:47.330
square over 2R squared.

01:01:47.330 --> 01:01:49.550
And if you do it
carefully here you

01:01:49.550 --> 01:01:51.710
see that this kills the square.

01:01:51.710 --> 01:01:53.420
This kills this.

01:01:53.420 --> 01:02:05.630
And you end up with s equals
minus x squared over 2R.

01:02:05.630 --> 01:02:08.340
And what this means now is
if you compare with equation

01:02:08.340 --> 01:02:12.770
of the ideal parabola,
which was x squared over 4F,

01:02:12.770 --> 01:02:17.000
it means that F
equals minus R over 2.

01:02:21.300 --> 01:02:23.220
The next question now
is what does this mean.

01:02:23.220 --> 01:02:25.610
Is the focal length
negative or positive?

01:02:28.570 --> 01:02:31.090
To answer this question,
we have to first remember

01:02:31.090 --> 01:02:32.830
our sign conventions.

01:02:32.830 --> 01:02:35.350
Is our surface
positive or negative?

01:02:35.350 --> 01:02:40.210
That is, is R a negative
or positive quantity?

01:02:40.210 --> 01:02:45.090
So if you recall, I'll go back
one slide to the previous one.

01:02:45.090 --> 01:02:47.640
This is a positive curvature.

01:02:47.640 --> 01:02:51.180
if If it is pointing that way,
I will not use any formal term

01:02:51.180 --> 01:02:52.560
because that may be confusing.

01:02:52.560 --> 01:02:56.890
If it's like that,
it's positive.

01:02:56.890 --> 01:02:58.000
This is not like that.

01:02:58.000 --> 01:02:58.850
It's the opposite.

01:02:58.850 --> 01:03:02.530
And so therefore
here, R is negative.

01:03:02.530 --> 01:03:05.770
So you have a negative sign
that came out of the math.

01:03:05.770 --> 01:03:08.140
But R is a negative quantity.

01:03:08.140 --> 01:03:10.750
So therefore F is
still positive.

01:03:10.750 --> 01:03:12.430
So this is still
a positive lens.

01:03:21.400 --> 01:03:23.800
And it is clear that
it is a positive lens,

01:03:23.800 --> 01:03:27.010
because it forms a real image
for an object at infinity.

01:03:27.010 --> 01:03:30.940
By construction, we demanded
that if I have parallel rays

01:03:30.940 --> 01:03:33.780
from infinity, these
things should focus them

01:03:33.780 --> 01:03:35.350
to a real point on the axis.

01:03:35.350 --> 01:03:37.450
So therefore,
clearly, this is what

01:03:37.450 --> 01:03:41.230
you would call a positive lens.

01:03:41.230 --> 01:03:43.690
And since the lens,
it actually has

01:03:43.690 --> 01:03:47.230
a matrix that is very similar
to the matrix of a lens,

01:03:47.230 --> 01:03:50.560
all you have to do is
substitute the focal length

01:03:50.560 --> 01:03:52.540
with the equation
that we just derived

01:03:52.540 --> 01:03:55.180
for the radius of curvature.

01:03:55.180 --> 01:04:00.640
And this is the matrix that
describes a mirror, a mirror

01:04:00.640 --> 01:04:02.510
concentrator.

01:04:02.510 --> 01:04:06.500
And of course, since it is a
lens, it also forms images.

01:04:09.080 --> 01:04:12.920
So notice here,
the way I drew it,

01:04:12.920 --> 01:04:15.200
these quantities are
still all positive.

01:04:15.200 --> 01:04:19.290
Of course, it's not as positive
because I go from the object

01:04:19.290 --> 01:04:23.620
to the right, towards
the instrument.

01:04:23.620 --> 01:04:24.700
Now notice what happens.

01:04:24.700 --> 01:04:28.930
From the instrument, I go to
the left towards the image.

01:04:28.930 --> 01:04:30.640
But that is still
a positive quantity

01:04:30.640 --> 01:04:33.520
because there was a reflection
that occurred there.

01:04:33.520 --> 01:04:37.780
So therefore s sub I is
still a positive quantity.

01:04:37.780 --> 01:04:40.570
So I can write this equation
with a clear conscience,

01:04:40.570 --> 01:04:48.350
so to speak, that s0 and si
are all positive qualities.

01:04:48.350 --> 01:04:53.150
Now can you imagine when a lens
might form a virtual image?

01:04:53.150 --> 01:04:56.335
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

