01:09:41.859 --> 01:09:47.819
So the magnifier, as
the name suggests,

01:09:47.819 --> 01:09:52.300
it is a device that we use
to aid our eyes when we're

01:09:52.300 --> 01:09:56.330
looking at a very small object.

01:09:56.330 --> 01:09:59.147
And this is a--

01:09:59.147 --> 01:10:01.230
dog it took me a lot of
time to make this cartoon.

01:10:01.230 --> 01:10:02.230
So I'm very proud of it.

01:10:02.230 --> 01:10:04.700
So let me start
the animation here.

01:10:04.700 --> 01:10:08.980
So if you have a really
small object, of course

01:10:08.980 --> 01:10:12.580
it will form a very small
image on your retina.

01:10:12.580 --> 01:10:16.030
And very often,
this image is not

01:10:16.030 --> 01:10:19.582
big enough to observe
with sufficient detail.

01:10:19.582 --> 01:10:21.040
So the obvious
thing that you would

01:10:21.040 --> 01:10:22.780
do if something
looks small to you

01:10:22.780 --> 01:10:24.843
and you'd like to
make it bigger,

01:10:24.843 --> 01:10:26.260
you don't have to
know any optics.

01:10:26.260 --> 01:10:28.295
What you do is you
bring it near your eyes.

01:10:28.295 --> 01:10:29.920
But from experience,
you know that this

01:10:29.920 --> 01:10:30.940
doesn't work very well.

01:10:30.940 --> 01:10:32.680
Because if you
exceed the distance

01:10:32.680 --> 01:10:35.980
of approximately 25
centimeters, then you

01:10:35.980 --> 01:10:37.780
can really not focus anymore.

01:10:37.780 --> 01:10:40.320
And actually for you
guys who are young

01:10:40.320 --> 01:10:42.730
it's about 25 centimeters.

01:10:42.730 --> 01:10:46.090
As we grow older, this distance
becomes longer and longer.

01:10:46.090 --> 01:10:47.530
And we basically
lose our ability

01:10:47.530 --> 01:10:49.840
to focus, which is a very
annoying, annoying thing

01:10:49.840 --> 01:10:50.440
actually.

01:10:50.440 --> 01:10:52.130
It has just started
to happen to me.

01:10:52.130 --> 01:10:55.840
As I approach age 40, I've
started noticing that I cannot

01:10:55.840 --> 01:10:57.920
focus as well as I used to.

01:10:57.920 --> 01:11:00.190
So it's a little bit annoying.

01:11:00.190 --> 01:11:02.800
But anyway it beats the
alternative I guess.

01:11:02.800 --> 01:11:04.550
So I'm very happy that
I reached that age.

01:11:04.550 --> 01:11:09.160
But anyway, the point is
that there comes a point--

01:11:09.160 --> 01:11:11.140
actually for me now,
the only way to focus

01:11:11.140 --> 01:11:13.600
is to take off my glasses.

01:11:13.600 --> 01:11:15.847
But even so, there
comes a point where

01:11:15.847 --> 01:11:16.930
you can not focus anymore.

01:11:16.930 --> 01:11:17.980
Even you cannot focus.

01:11:17.980 --> 01:11:21.790
I bring something to 5 or 10
centimeters, you cannot focus.

01:11:21.790 --> 01:11:23.900
The question is,
what could you do.

01:11:23.900 --> 01:11:25.905
So what you do is
you use a magnifier.

01:11:25.905 --> 01:11:27.610
And the magnifier is
something that you

01:11:27.610 --> 01:11:30.820
put between the
object and your eye.

01:11:30.820 --> 01:11:33.340
And the way it
works is like this.

01:11:33.340 --> 01:11:35.350
We can do some simple
ray tracing here.

01:11:38.170 --> 01:11:40.500
This is where the
parameters of the magnifier,

01:11:40.500 --> 01:11:45.760
let's say it is a positive
lens, the magnifier.

01:11:45.760 --> 01:11:47.750
Let's say the focal
length is F and the power

01:11:47.750 --> 01:11:49.560
is the inverse of that.

01:11:49.560 --> 01:11:54.530
So this is some ray tracing
that shows how the image is

01:11:54.530 --> 01:11:56.120
formed by this lens.

01:11:56.120 --> 01:11:58.730
So all you do is you
take a horizontal ray.

01:11:58.730 --> 01:12:00.450
This will go somehow through--

01:12:00.450 --> 01:12:02.330
this guy will bend it.

01:12:02.330 --> 01:12:06.770
And let's pretend now that
this ray, somehow I tune things

01:12:06.770 --> 01:12:09.740
so that this ray went through
the center of the eye.

01:12:09.740 --> 01:12:11.770
So this ray went
and bend, right?

01:12:11.770 --> 01:12:15.620
But you can see very clearly
now because what these lines did

01:12:15.620 --> 01:12:18.290
is it bent this ray
bundle so that it

01:12:18.290 --> 01:12:20.030
meets the object over here.

01:12:20.030 --> 01:12:25.160
The result is that I got a much
magnified image on the retina.

01:12:25.160 --> 01:12:25.980
That's about it.

01:12:25.980 --> 01:12:27.460
That's all there is to.

01:12:27.460 --> 01:12:30.860
By using this element,
you can get bigger images.

01:12:30.860 --> 01:12:34.540
Now if I didn't
have the eye here,

01:12:34.540 --> 01:12:37.410
this is actually the
most instructive thing

01:12:37.410 --> 01:12:39.790
I'm going to say today.

01:12:39.790 --> 01:12:42.880
This is really the meaning
of the virtual image.

01:12:42.880 --> 01:12:46.870
If I give you this system
by itself, obviously

01:12:46.870 --> 01:12:49.040
because this lens, if
you look carefully,

01:12:49.040 --> 01:12:51.740
it created a
divergent ray bundle.

01:12:51.740 --> 01:12:56.830
Obviously this object is between
the focal point of the lens.

01:12:56.830 --> 01:12:58.330
So therefore, this
is the situation

01:12:58.330 --> 01:13:00.070
that we encountered before.

01:13:00.070 --> 01:13:03.370
And we've said that the
system forms a virtual image.

01:13:03.370 --> 01:13:05.230
Well what is the virtual image?

01:13:05.230 --> 01:13:07.450
I have to take these rays
that the lens produced

01:13:07.450 --> 01:13:09.880
and I have to extend
them backwards.

01:13:09.880 --> 01:13:11.590
And with a little
bit of manipulation

01:13:11.590 --> 01:13:15.210
here, because this is a cartoon,
it is not a real calculation.

01:13:15.210 --> 01:13:16.840
But with some
manipulation, I made sure

01:13:16.840 --> 01:13:18.220
that the rays do meet.

01:13:18.220 --> 01:13:19.460
So the rays meet.

01:13:19.460 --> 01:13:23.020
And the point where the rays
meet is the virtual image.

01:13:23.020 --> 01:13:24.880
There's nothing there.

01:13:24.880 --> 01:13:25.540
Nothing.

01:13:25.540 --> 01:13:26.530
The object is here.

01:13:26.530 --> 01:13:29.410
The only physical entity
is here and your eye,

01:13:29.410 --> 01:13:30.760
and the lens of course.

01:13:30.760 --> 01:13:31.900
There's nothing here.

01:13:31.900 --> 01:13:37.280
But when your eye
forms an image it

01:13:37.280 --> 01:13:40.730
is as if you could
take this away--

01:13:40.730 --> 01:13:43.070
you could take away the
combination of the object

01:13:43.070 --> 01:13:48.410
and the magnifier and replace
it with a virtual image

01:13:48.410 --> 01:13:50.660
that this system formed.

01:13:50.660 --> 01:13:57.550
This virtual element is acting
as an object for your eye.

01:13:57.550 --> 01:13:59.380
The eye images this object.

01:13:59.380 --> 01:14:03.010
And because this object
has been magnified relative

01:14:03.010 --> 01:14:08.930
to the actual object, you end
up observing a magnified image.

01:14:08.930 --> 01:14:11.080
So this is the significance
of virtual images.

01:14:11.080 --> 01:14:13.570
By themselves, that
don't mean anything.

01:14:13.570 --> 01:14:17.080
But because at the end of an
optical system you always have

01:14:17.080 --> 01:14:19.830
the observer's--

01:14:19.830 --> 01:14:21.700
I mean, the
observer's eye length

01:14:21.700 --> 01:14:24.570
and the retina,
the virtual image

01:14:24.570 --> 01:14:28.390
ends up becoming a real image,
hopefully on the retina.

01:14:28.390 --> 01:14:30.698
If it becomes a real
image elsewhere,

01:14:30.698 --> 01:14:31.990
you will not be able to see it.

01:14:31.990 --> 01:14:33.490
It will be out to focus.

01:14:33.490 --> 01:14:35.440
Or even worse, if you
create a virtual image

01:14:35.440 --> 01:14:37.570
and you send it to an
observer so it becomes

01:14:37.570 --> 01:14:39.430
a virtual image on
the retina, again you

01:14:39.430 --> 01:14:40.472
don't see anything there.

01:14:40.472 --> 01:14:43.750
Because you can never
observe a virtual image

01:14:43.750 --> 01:14:47.170
unless you can image it
using the optics of your eye.

01:14:47.170 --> 01:14:49.790
So this is the
significance then.

01:14:49.790 --> 01:14:52.870
And we'll see in the second
that everything-- microscopes,

01:14:52.870 --> 01:14:54.790
telescopes, magnifiers--

01:14:54.790 --> 01:14:59.710
they all form of virtual images
which eventually the observer's

01:14:59.710 --> 01:15:02.640
eye lens converts to a
real image on the retina.

01:15:07.240 --> 01:15:08.770
The next thing that
we'll do now is

01:15:08.770 --> 01:15:13.120
we'll put some math
around this topic.

01:15:13.120 --> 01:15:14.620
And this is a little
bit unfortunate

01:15:14.620 --> 01:15:18.180
because the book is generally
very good, the textbook

01:15:18.180 --> 01:15:20.050
that we have, Hecht.

01:15:20.050 --> 01:15:22.180
I do think that in
this particular topic,

01:15:22.180 --> 01:15:24.590
the textbook is a
little bit confusing.

01:15:24.590 --> 01:15:27.610
So I'll try to walk you through
the derivation in the textbook

01:15:27.610 --> 01:15:32.190
and hopefully I will
make it less confusing.

01:15:32.190 --> 01:15:38.310
But if, when you go back home
and you read the textbook,

01:15:38.310 --> 01:15:41.460
you confused again, please
bring your questions on Monday

01:15:41.460 --> 01:15:44.730
so we can talk about this again.

01:15:44.730 --> 01:15:47.310
So I tried to make
it less confusing

01:15:47.310 --> 01:15:50.070
but still I'm using the
notation in the book.

01:15:50.070 --> 01:15:53.520
So you don't-- in addition
to the confusion in the book,

01:15:53.520 --> 01:15:57.200
you don't have to overcome
notational confusion.

01:15:59.800 --> 01:16:04.720
So the definition of the
magnifying power which cannot

01:16:04.720 --> 01:16:08.810
be argued against because it is
a definition is it is the ratio

01:16:08.810 --> 01:16:13.870
of the angle subtended by
the tip of the object before

01:16:13.870 --> 01:16:15.610
and after magnification.

01:16:15.610 --> 01:16:19.570
Actually the subscript
here, U and A, U

01:16:19.570 --> 01:16:23.800
stands for Unaided, that is
the eye without the magnifier.

01:16:23.800 --> 01:16:25.930
And A stands for Aided.

01:16:25.930 --> 01:16:32.140
That is the eye with the
aid of the magnifier lens.

01:16:32.140 --> 01:16:40.280
And now we need to place symbols
to all of these distances here.

01:16:40.280 --> 01:16:42.530
And I think this is where
the book is a bit confusing.

01:16:42.530 --> 01:16:44.780
Because it tries to
do everything at once.

01:16:44.780 --> 01:16:47.030
But anyway, so I
need this symbol

01:16:47.030 --> 01:16:50.290
for the distance between
the object of the lens.

01:16:50.290 --> 01:16:53.760
Then I need the symbol
from the lens to the eye.

01:16:53.760 --> 01:16:57.230
And in the symbol from the lens
to the virtual image, which

01:16:57.230 --> 01:16:59.720
is of course si,
and in this case

01:16:59.720 --> 01:17:01.400
you would expect
the side to turn out

01:17:01.400 --> 01:17:04.340
to be a negative number,
because it is a virtual image.

01:17:04.340 --> 01:17:07.490
And finally you use the
symbol L for the distance

01:17:07.490 --> 01:17:12.920
between the virtual
image and the eye.

01:17:12.920 --> 01:17:15.710
So L is, of course, that simply
the sum of these two distances

01:17:15.710 --> 01:17:18.300
with a proper sign convention.

01:17:24.130 --> 01:17:26.130
The first thing to note
is that you don't really

01:17:26.130 --> 01:17:30.150
need all these notations
because the magnifying power is

01:17:30.150 --> 01:17:32.790
very simple to calculate.

01:17:32.790 --> 01:17:36.300
As we did in the past,
all you have to do

01:17:36.300 --> 01:17:39.000
is use similar triangles.

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:44.820
Because you can see that
the magnifying power--

01:17:47.550 --> 01:17:51.390
the angle a sub a,
the [INAUDIBLE] angle,

01:17:51.390 --> 01:17:57.490
equals the ratio of the size
of the virtual image over what?

01:17:57.490 --> 01:18:00.240
Look at the red line.

01:18:00.240 --> 01:18:04.317
From this ray angle,
over the big distance L.

01:18:04.317 --> 01:18:05.650
And of course there's a tangent.

01:18:05.650 --> 01:18:06.700
I should have a tangent there.

01:18:06.700 --> 01:18:08.200
But I dropped the
tangent because

01:18:08.200 --> 01:18:10.330
of the paraxial approximation.

01:18:10.330 --> 01:18:16.210
Similarly for the
unaided eye, it

01:18:16.210 --> 01:18:19.990
equals the ratio of the
natural height of the object

01:18:19.990 --> 01:18:23.140
to the distance between
the object and the lens.

01:18:23.140 --> 01:18:28.150
Now for the unaided case, the
convention is to use the near

01:18:28.150 --> 01:18:32.230
point of the eye, that is the
25 centimeter distance beyond

01:18:32.230 --> 01:18:33.550
which the eye cannot focus.

01:18:33.550 --> 01:18:35.770
Because presumably,
if you wanted

01:18:35.770 --> 01:18:39.232
to get the maximum possible
unaided magnification,

01:18:39.232 --> 01:18:40.690
you really have to
bring the object

01:18:40.690 --> 01:18:43.780
within this 25 centimeters.

01:18:43.780 --> 01:18:45.880
So that's why we use d0.

01:18:45.880 --> 01:18:47.200
So that's a standard actually.

01:18:47.200 --> 01:18:49.600
It is 25 centimeters.

01:18:49.600 --> 01:18:51.350
And when you play
around with this,

01:18:51.350 --> 01:18:53.830
you discover that it equals
the ratio of these two

01:18:53.830 --> 01:18:57.140
distances, which is easy to do.

01:18:57.140 --> 01:18:59.150
And this is what
we used to call--

01:18:59.150 --> 01:19:01.250
what did we call
this quantity when

01:19:01.250 --> 01:19:04.730
we did the imaging condition?

01:19:07.610 --> 01:19:08.570
Button.

01:19:08.570 --> 01:19:10.060
AUDIENCE: Lateral magnification.

01:19:10.060 --> 01:19:11.060
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:19:11.060 --> 01:19:13.730
This is what we used to call
the lateral magnification.

01:19:13.730 --> 01:19:16.360
It is the ratio of
the size of the image

01:19:16.360 --> 01:19:19.970
over the size of the object.

01:19:19.970 --> 01:19:24.250
So this is what they say here.

01:19:24.250 --> 01:19:26.820
And of course this is the
lateral magnification.

01:19:26.820 --> 01:19:28.510
We have the questions
for it in terms

01:19:28.510 --> 01:19:30.760
of the image and distances.

01:19:30.760 --> 01:19:35.920
And we can substitute
these equations

01:19:35.920 --> 01:19:37.450
and we can actually
derive a number

01:19:37.450 --> 01:19:40.970
of equivalent expressions
for the magnifying power.

01:19:40.970 --> 01:19:43.870
So now, none of this is
particularly intuitive.

01:19:43.870 --> 01:19:46.210
And then the book goes
ahead and gives two

01:19:46.210 --> 01:19:49.450
possible uses of
the magnifying lens

01:19:49.450 --> 01:19:52.750
that are not particularly
intuitive either.

01:19:52.750 --> 01:19:55.130
So I will not even
bother to deal with them.

01:19:55.130 --> 01:19:57.800
One of them is when
you put the magnifier

01:19:57.800 --> 01:19:59.380
one focal distance away.

01:20:03.230 --> 01:20:05.210
I don't know if it's
necessary to do that.

01:20:05.210 --> 01:20:08.100
The other is when you
put the magnifier--

01:20:08.100 --> 01:20:10.463
you stick it to your eye,
which is not a very good idea

01:20:10.463 --> 01:20:11.880
because there's
all kinds of germs

01:20:11.880 --> 01:20:14.710
around so you don't
want to stick magnifiers

01:20:14.710 --> 01:20:17.200
onto your body.

01:20:17.200 --> 01:20:20.760
The way we use
magnifiers in general

01:20:20.760 --> 01:20:24.960
is the number three
description of the book, which

01:20:24.960 --> 01:20:27.690
is why we place the
object at one focal point

01:20:27.690 --> 01:20:29.640
behind the magnifier.

01:20:29.640 --> 01:20:34.228
So if the magnifying focal
length is 5 centimeters--

01:20:34.228 --> 01:20:35.520
actually, that's a pretty long.

01:20:35.520 --> 01:20:39.240
But anyway, you place it 5
centimeters from the object.

01:20:39.240 --> 01:20:42.120
What do you accomplish this way?

01:20:42.120 --> 01:20:45.260
What happens if you place an
object at one focal distance

01:20:45.260 --> 01:20:48.370
in front of the lens.

01:20:48.370 --> 01:20:49.210
That's right.

01:20:49.210 --> 01:20:50.680
You form an image at infinity.

01:20:50.680 --> 01:20:53.950
Actually, in that case, you
form a real image with infinity.

01:20:53.950 --> 01:20:54.950
Now is that good or bad?

01:20:59.490 --> 01:21:02.640
In the context here, you
form the image with infinity

01:21:02.640 --> 01:21:06.810
and you still have an
observer with his or her eye

01:21:06.810 --> 01:21:07.680
lens and the retina.

01:21:10.810 --> 01:21:11.980
Let me draw this.

01:21:16.720 --> 01:21:20.190
Now we draw the specific case,
according to the book lingo,

01:21:20.190 --> 01:21:25.140
this is case number
three, si equals F.

01:21:25.140 --> 01:21:26.380
So what does it look like?

01:21:26.380 --> 01:21:27.600
Here's my magnifier.

01:21:31.160 --> 01:21:36.110
Here is my eye lens.

01:21:36.110 --> 01:21:38.982
And of course the eye
kind of looks like this.

01:21:38.982 --> 01:21:39.940
And this is the retina.

01:21:44.410 --> 01:21:48.490
And here is the optical axis.

01:21:48.490 --> 01:21:51.825
And here is the object.

01:21:51.825 --> 01:21:53.450
So let's look at the
tip of the object.

01:21:53.450 --> 01:21:59.000
Since it is one focal
distance away from the lens

01:21:59.000 --> 01:22:01.225
I will get a
parallel ray bundle.

01:22:05.530 --> 01:22:07.240
Is that good or bad?

01:22:07.240 --> 01:22:08.980
AUDIENCE: It's s0
equals F, right?

01:22:12.144 --> 01:22:12.890
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:22:12.890 --> 01:22:13.390
Thank you.

01:22:19.792 --> 01:22:20.750
So is that good or bad?

01:22:23.516 --> 01:22:26.995
AUDIENCE: If we talk of
aberrations, it's good.

01:22:26.995 --> 01:22:27.810
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:22:27.810 --> 01:22:30.100
Let's not go into aberrations.

01:22:30.100 --> 01:22:32.040
In our simple
geometrical optics,

01:22:32.040 --> 01:22:34.140
is that situation happy?

01:22:34.140 --> 01:22:37.012
Are we happy that we did this?

01:22:37.012 --> 01:22:39.115
We're happy for a
number of reasons.

01:22:39.115 --> 01:22:40.000
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:22:40.000 --> 01:22:43.380
Because it will perfectly
focus at the point.

01:22:43.380 --> 01:22:44.380
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:22:44.380 --> 01:22:49.340
First of all, this is assumed
to be a corrected eye.

01:22:49.340 --> 01:22:55.710
So if it was me, that would
be me wearing my eyeglasses.

01:22:55.710 --> 01:22:58.020
If it is me without my
eyeglasses, I have a problem.

01:22:58.020 --> 01:22:59.980
You'll see in a
second what problem.

01:22:59.980 --> 01:23:06.135
But if it is a
healthy eyesight where

01:23:06.135 --> 01:23:08.010
the eye can focus
perfectly, then this indeed

01:23:08.010 --> 01:23:09.420
will form an image
on the retina.

01:23:12.930 --> 01:23:17.130
What is the other good
news about this situation?

01:23:17.130 --> 01:23:19.740
The fact that the
image is at infinity,

01:23:19.740 --> 01:23:20.990
is this good news or bad news?

01:23:26.138 --> 01:23:27.990
AUDIENCE: Your eyes remain--

01:23:27.990 --> 01:23:29.925
your eye remains unaccommodated.

01:23:29.925 --> 01:23:31.920
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:23:31.920 --> 01:23:37.150
We learned that the eye is
most relaxed when it observes

01:23:37.150 --> 01:23:39.790
remote objects at infinity.

01:23:39.790 --> 01:23:42.330
The reason it cannot focus
closer is because I have

01:23:42.330 --> 01:23:44.690
to strain the lens of my eye.

01:23:44.690 --> 01:23:49.140
And as I get older, my ability
to strain it diminishes.

01:23:49.140 --> 01:23:51.888
But this is true for
everybody, young or old.

01:23:51.888 --> 01:23:53.680
When you try to look
at something close by,

01:23:53.680 --> 01:23:55.260
you get tired.

01:23:55.260 --> 01:23:58.080
If you read a book like
this, your parents probably

01:23:58.080 --> 01:23:59.080
told you-- they told me.

01:23:59.080 --> 01:24:01.247
Don't read the book like
this, you get the headache.

01:24:01.247 --> 01:24:02.080
And indeed you do.

01:24:02.080 --> 01:24:06.300
If you read for a long time you
get a headache from very close.

01:24:06.300 --> 01:24:08.970
So the reason this
is a happy situation

01:24:08.970 --> 01:24:12.180
is because the eye
can be totally relaxed

01:24:12.180 --> 01:24:15.650
as if it was observing
something very far away

01:24:15.650 --> 01:24:19.940
and still see the object
with magnification.

01:24:19.940 --> 01:24:21.800
And how much is
the magnification?

01:24:21.800 --> 01:24:24.240
Well, we'll skip the math.

01:24:24.240 --> 01:24:25.850
The math is fairly simple here.

01:24:25.850 --> 01:24:29.960
But it turns out to be simply
the product of the near point,

01:24:29.960 --> 01:24:34.670
the 25 centimeters, times
their power of the lens.

01:24:34.670 --> 01:24:37.010
And the only penalty
you pay, the reason,

01:24:37.010 --> 01:24:39.670
actually, the book covers
this case over here

01:24:39.670 --> 01:24:42.440
is because this is not the
maximum magnification you

01:24:42.440 --> 01:24:44.090
can get with a magnifier.

01:24:44.090 --> 01:24:47.550
You can get slightly higher
if you stick the magnifier

01:24:47.550 --> 01:24:48.270
next to your eye.

01:24:51.253 --> 01:24:53.170
But you never stick the
magnifier to your eye,

01:24:53.170 --> 01:24:53.740
actually.

01:24:53.740 --> 01:24:56.524
Unless you're adventurous.

01:24:59.710 --> 01:25:01.960
If I did this, I would
damage my glasses.

01:25:06.480 --> 01:25:08.760
So the message,
perhaps, important.

01:25:08.760 --> 01:25:13.800
But what I really hope
that you get out of this

01:25:13.800 --> 01:25:17.280
is the significance
of the virtual image

01:25:17.280 --> 01:25:21.600
and why the magnifier functions
by forming a virtual image that

01:25:21.600 --> 01:25:23.940
is erect and magnified.

01:25:23.940 --> 01:25:28.880
And this also tells you why
you will use a positive lens

01:25:28.880 --> 01:25:30.410
as a magnifier.

01:25:30.410 --> 01:25:33.610
If you recall, it is actually
one of the previous slides.

01:25:33.610 --> 01:25:35.870
A negative lens also
forms a virtual image.

01:25:35.870 --> 01:25:38.740
But unfortunately,
it is not magnified.

01:25:38.740 --> 01:25:41.570
The magnification,
it is de-magnified.

01:25:41.570 --> 01:25:44.110
The lateral magnification
is less than 1.

01:25:44.110 --> 01:25:46.280
So we would be out
of luck in this case.

01:25:58.040 --> 01:26:03.000
The next element is
actually the same.

01:26:03.000 --> 01:26:05.270
It is no different
than the magnifier.

01:26:05.270 --> 01:26:08.060
But it comes under
the name eyepiece

01:26:08.060 --> 01:26:13.640
because in optical instruments
such as binoculars, telescopes,

01:26:13.640 --> 01:26:18.680
microscopes, and the like
this is the last lens

01:26:18.680 --> 01:26:23.840
that you look into the
instrument with your naked eye.

01:26:23.840 --> 01:26:27.410
Now I realize that this
is old fashioned talk.

01:26:27.410 --> 01:26:31.640
Modern instruments, you seldom
look at with a naked eye.

01:26:31.640 --> 01:26:33.500
You actually have a camera.

01:26:33.500 --> 01:26:36.050
So you put a digital camera
and you register the image

01:26:36.050 --> 01:26:37.070
digitally.

01:26:37.070 --> 01:26:39.670
However, even a digital camera
functions like a retina.

01:26:39.670 --> 01:26:41.810
So in other words,
even a digital camera

01:26:41.810 --> 01:26:45.140
would have an eyepiece
and then a condenser.

01:26:45.140 --> 01:26:47.760
And then it would
go onto the chip.

01:26:47.760 --> 01:26:51.950
So really the situation here
applies to digital imaging

01:26:51.950 --> 01:26:56.540
as well as human, as
well as instruments

01:26:56.540 --> 01:26:59.820
meant to be used by humans.

01:26:59.820 --> 01:27:06.150
So the eyepiece is basically the
last element in the instrument,

01:27:06.150 --> 01:27:12.710
just before you get to the
actual observation stage.

01:27:12.710 --> 01:27:16.580
And because the eyepieces
were traditionally

01:27:16.580 --> 01:27:20.180
designed for the humans,
they are typically

01:27:20.180 --> 01:27:23.100
designed like a magnifier
with the same principle

01:27:23.100 --> 01:27:27.300
that I described before that
forms an image of infinity.

01:27:27.300 --> 01:27:29.900
So therefore the
observer, when he or she

01:27:29.900 --> 01:27:35.510
looks into the eyepiece, they
can use an unaccommodated eye

01:27:35.510 --> 01:27:40.010
and observe the magnified
image without having

01:27:40.010 --> 01:27:42.110
to strain their eyes.

01:27:42.110 --> 01:27:48.980
So this is the sort of
standard use of an eyepiece.

01:27:48.980 --> 01:27:54.350
And there's a second condition
for the eyepiece which

01:27:54.350 --> 01:28:02.750
will become a little bit more
apparent in the next slide

01:28:02.750 --> 01:28:05.000
when I talk about
the microscope.

01:28:05.000 --> 01:28:06.290
It is this one over here.

01:28:08.997 --> 01:28:10.330
This looks a little bit cryptic.

01:28:10.330 --> 01:28:13.810
It says the center of
the exit pupil eyepoint

01:28:13.810 --> 01:28:17.957
where the observer's eye
is placed at 10 millimeters

01:28:17.957 --> 01:28:18.790
from the instrument.

01:28:18.790 --> 01:28:19.748
This doesn't mean much.

01:28:19.748 --> 01:28:23.260
But I will describe what
this means in a second, when

01:28:23.260 --> 01:28:24.520
I talk about the microscope.

01:28:24.520 --> 01:28:28.600
Not withstanding this last
point over here, any questions

01:28:28.600 --> 01:28:31.328
about the eyepiece or
the magnifier or anything

01:28:31.328 --> 01:28:31.870
of that sort?

01:28:41.156 --> 01:28:44.780
AUDIENCE: Why is the eye
[INAUDIBLE] 10 millimeter when

01:28:44.780 --> 01:28:45.620
we cannot see?

01:28:47.877 --> 01:28:48.460
PROFESSOR: OK.

01:28:48.460 --> 01:28:52.290
What this really means is that
10 millimeters is the design

01:28:52.290 --> 01:28:55.420
distance that you're supposed
to place your eyes with respect

01:28:55.420 --> 01:28:57.340
to the instrument.

01:28:57.340 --> 01:29:00.087
When you look at the microscope,
for example, most people

01:29:00.087 --> 01:29:00.670
don't do that.

01:29:00.670 --> 01:29:02.950
But you're supposed to be
at about 10 centimeters

01:29:02.950 --> 01:29:06.430
from the last surface, right?

01:29:06.430 --> 01:29:10.030
So that is called
the eye relief.

01:29:10.030 --> 01:29:13.660
And what this is really saying
is that when you look at this,

01:29:13.660 --> 01:29:19.540
you're not supposed to see
any blockage of the image.

01:29:19.540 --> 01:29:22.452
And you're not supposed
to see vignetting.

01:29:22.452 --> 01:29:23.910
There's two things
that can happen.

01:29:23.910 --> 01:29:26.202
If you place your eye at the
wrong point-- as you know,

01:29:26.202 --> 01:29:28.340
if any of you have
looked at a microscope,

01:29:28.340 --> 01:29:31.380
if you are not positioned
properly you cannot see

01:29:31.380 --> 01:29:32.460
the entire field of view.

01:29:32.460 --> 01:29:33.360
That's one problem.

01:29:33.360 --> 01:29:35.412
You see a black hole.

01:29:35.412 --> 01:29:36.870
And you kind of
have to move around

01:29:36.870 --> 01:29:38.550
and you can never see
anything until you

01:29:38.550 --> 01:29:41.847
go to the proper place and then
finally you see everything.

01:29:41.847 --> 01:29:42.930
So this is the eye relief.

01:29:42.930 --> 01:29:45.927
This is by design where
you should place your eye.

01:29:45.927 --> 01:29:47.760
The other thing that
can happen if you place

01:29:47.760 --> 01:29:50.220
your eye at the wrong place
or if the microscope is not

01:29:50.220 --> 01:29:52.200
properly designed is vignetting.

01:29:52.200 --> 01:29:55.080
So this requirement
clearly assures

01:29:55.080 --> 01:29:59.210
that there's no vignetting
when your eye is placed

01:29:59.210 --> 01:30:01.950
at eye relief distance,
that is at 10 millimeters

01:30:01.950 --> 01:30:03.090
from the instrument.

01:30:03.090 --> 01:30:04.020
And of course, you
don't have to worry

01:30:04.020 --> 01:30:06.660
about focusing because the
microscope is supposed to have

01:30:06.660 --> 01:30:08.130
infinite conjugate, right?

01:30:08.130 --> 01:30:11.790
So you just use with
an accommodated eye.

01:30:11.790 --> 01:30:13.857
And I suspect, I don't
know if it's true,

01:30:13.857 --> 01:30:16.190
but I suspect-- there are
many reasons why they put over

01:30:16.190 --> 01:30:16.670
there.

01:30:16.670 --> 01:30:18.837
But also, it's kind of
convenient that when you look

01:30:18.837 --> 01:30:21.830
at the microscope you're so
close to the microscope tube

01:30:21.830 --> 01:30:24.360
itself that you cannot focus
and you cannot see that.

01:30:24.360 --> 01:30:25.860
So you can basically
see what you're

01:30:25.860 --> 01:30:28.318
supposed to observe but you
don't see the actual instrument

01:30:28.318 --> 01:30:29.730
because it is out of focus.

01:30:29.730 --> 01:30:30.965
So that's kind of convenient.

01:30:33.580 --> 01:30:35.480
So [INAUDIBLE] this
about the microscope.

01:30:35.480 --> 01:30:36.730
Here is a microscope.

01:30:36.730 --> 01:30:39.340
Here's what it looks like.

01:30:39.340 --> 01:30:40.440
It is deceptively simple.

01:30:40.440 --> 01:30:43.620
Because there's, of course,
a lot of engineering design

01:30:43.620 --> 01:30:46.410
that goes into making
all of these elements.

01:30:46.410 --> 01:30:48.420
But the principle is
surprisingly simple.

01:30:48.420 --> 01:30:51.180
It consists of basically
two magnifiers.

01:30:51.180 --> 01:30:53.840
One of them is called objective.

01:30:53.840 --> 01:30:55.230
The other is called eyepiece.

01:30:55.230 --> 01:30:58.650
But they both function
as magnifiers.

01:30:58.650 --> 01:31:02.710
So the job of the objective,
this is the first lens.

01:31:02.710 --> 01:31:06.390
It is called objective because
it is placed near the object.

01:31:06.390 --> 01:31:12.120
And its job is basically to
form an intermediate image that

01:31:12.120 --> 01:31:14.550
is magnified to begin with.

01:31:14.550 --> 01:31:15.990
What is it magnified by?

01:31:15.990 --> 01:31:19.020
Well, here we simply have--

01:31:19.020 --> 01:31:20.670
actually this is a real image.

01:31:20.670 --> 01:31:23.980
So we simply have a positive
lens forming a real image.

01:31:23.980 --> 01:31:26.100
We can compute
the magnification.

01:31:26.100 --> 01:31:34.340
It is equal to minus si over s0,
just like the regular formula.

01:31:34.340 --> 01:31:39.170
And then we have the
eyepiece for which

01:31:39.170 --> 01:31:44.000
the image that the objective
produced actually now

01:31:44.000 --> 01:31:45.980
acts as the object.

01:31:45.980 --> 01:31:50.180
So this intermediate image
is re-imaged by the eyepiece.

01:31:50.180 --> 01:31:52.980
But the eyepiece is
placed one focal distance.

01:31:52.980 --> 01:31:56.960
F sub e here is the focal
length of the eyepiece.

01:31:56.960 --> 01:32:00.530
It is one focal distance
from that intermediate image.

01:32:00.530 --> 01:32:06.310
And therefore the final
image is formed at infinity.

01:32:06.310 --> 01:32:12.370
Now the way this is
drawn for this one, what

01:32:12.370 --> 01:32:16.480
is prominent in this picture
is, of course, the on-axis ray.

01:32:16.480 --> 01:32:19.330
And there's no
magnification to talk about

01:32:19.330 --> 01:32:20.830
because this is just an axis.

01:32:20.830 --> 01:32:22.270
Nothing interesting
is happening.

01:32:22.270 --> 01:32:23.770
What is really
interesting is if you

01:32:23.770 --> 01:32:26.680
look at an off-axis point,
which is at the bottom here.

01:32:26.680 --> 01:32:28.650
It's a little bit
difficult to see.

01:32:28.650 --> 01:32:30.882
It looks better in
the book actually.

01:32:30.882 --> 01:32:34.200
So if you trace
this off-axis point,

01:32:34.200 --> 01:32:36.330
then you find that
its final image

01:32:36.330 --> 01:32:40.860
is this ray bundle
that is coming off-axis

01:32:40.860 --> 01:32:44.820
into your eye,
this parallel ray.

01:32:44.820 --> 01:32:48.020
That is the final image
of the microscope produced

01:32:48.020 --> 01:32:50.580
of this off-axis
objective point.

01:32:50.580 --> 01:32:53.700
You can see it has entered
the eye at a very large angle.

01:32:53.700 --> 01:32:56.120
Therefore it will
form a big image.

01:32:56.120 --> 01:32:59.632
So that's how the microscope
magnifies small objects

01:32:59.632 --> 01:33:00.840
so that you can observe them.

01:33:05.060 --> 01:33:09.490
So then the magnification
of the microscope,

01:33:09.490 --> 01:33:11.860
very similar to the
case of the objective,

01:33:11.860 --> 01:33:15.610
is defined as the ratio
of this angle, the angle

01:33:15.610 --> 01:33:20.350
that the microscope produced
for the off-axis object,

01:33:20.350 --> 01:33:28.820
for the same angle that the
eye would observe unaided,

01:33:28.820 --> 01:33:32.210
in a very similar
case as the magnifier.

01:33:32.210 --> 01:33:36.450
So in order to compute this now,
it's not very difficult to do.

01:33:36.450 --> 01:33:37.980
We need two elements.

01:33:37.980 --> 01:33:40.250
One is the lateral
magnification of the objective.

01:33:40.250 --> 01:33:43.850
Because recall, the objective
actually forms a real image.

01:33:43.850 --> 01:33:45.860
So we have one.

01:33:45.860 --> 01:33:47.240
Here is the object.

01:33:47.240 --> 01:33:48.950
And here is its image.

01:33:48.950 --> 01:33:50.600
So we need, first
of all, to find out

01:33:50.600 --> 01:33:54.710
where the intermediate
image appears with respect

01:33:54.710 --> 01:33:55.880
to the optical axis.

01:33:55.880 --> 01:33:58.920
That's the lateral
magnification of the objective.

01:33:58.920 --> 01:34:02.630
That is whatever.

01:34:02.630 --> 01:34:06.660
Well, I will say in the
second why this 160 appears.

01:34:06.660 --> 01:34:12.260
But the second
element that we need

01:34:12.260 --> 01:34:15.380
is the angular magnification
of the eyepiece.

01:34:15.380 --> 01:34:20.180
Because this will allow us to
say how this distance over here

01:34:20.180 --> 01:34:26.150
translates into angle that
goes into the eye finally.

01:34:26.150 --> 01:34:30.330
So this one is actually
a familiar formula.

01:34:30.330 --> 01:34:33.300
This is the same formula
you had for the magnifier.

01:34:33.300 --> 01:34:35.570
So go back one.

01:34:35.570 --> 01:34:39.460
We said that-- actually,
it is over here already.

01:34:39.460 --> 01:34:40.940
We said that the
magnifying power

01:34:40.940 --> 01:34:45.950
of an eyepiece or a magnifier
equals the near distance

01:34:45.950 --> 01:34:51.950
for the eye, which is about 25
centimeters, times the power

01:34:51.950 --> 01:34:54.690
of the lens, of the
positive lens that they use.

01:34:54.690 --> 01:34:56.140
So this is the same formula.

01:34:56.140 --> 01:34:58.880
In microscopes, they don't
use exactly 25 centimeters.

01:34:58.880 --> 01:35:02.120
They use 25.4 centimeters.

01:35:02.120 --> 01:35:03.318
So this is the standard.

01:35:03.318 --> 01:35:04.610
And how much is that in inches?

01:35:04.610 --> 01:35:05.660
Is it 10 inches?

01:35:05.660 --> 01:35:07.090
No.

01:35:07.090 --> 01:35:09.220
11, 12 inches.

01:35:09.220 --> 01:35:10.510
10 inches.

01:35:10.510 --> 01:35:13.070
I thought it would be
22-- oh, that's pounds.

01:35:13.070 --> 01:35:13.570
I'm sorry.

01:35:13.570 --> 01:35:16.440
That's pounds.

01:35:16.440 --> 01:35:19.400
There's 10 inches then.

01:35:19.400 --> 01:35:21.350
So this is, then,
the same formula

01:35:21.350 --> 01:35:23.700
that we had for the magnifier.

01:35:23.700 --> 01:35:25.420
Where did this come from?

01:35:25.420 --> 01:35:27.600
Well, if you remember
one of the ways

01:35:27.600 --> 01:35:34.010
to add the lateral
magnification is like this--

01:35:34.010 --> 01:35:42.340
1 minus si over F. So you
can write this as 1 minus si

01:35:42.340 --> 01:35:50.320
over F equals F minus si
over F. And now I have to--

01:35:55.120 --> 01:35:56.230
Ah, that worked.

01:35:59.020 --> 01:36:00.210
So minus si--

01:36:00.210 --> 01:36:01.600
I am sorry.

01:36:01.600 --> 01:36:10.650
It is F minus si
over F. So F minus si

01:36:10.650 --> 01:36:23.066
is actually the distance between
the objective lens and the--

01:36:25.732 --> 01:36:27.860
it's basically this
distance L. That's

01:36:27.860 --> 01:36:29.050
what I'm trying to get to.

01:36:29.050 --> 01:36:31.700
So this is known as the tube
length of the microscope.

01:36:31.700 --> 01:36:36.290
It is the distance between the
objective lens and the location

01:36:36.290 --> 01:36:38.977
where you put the eyepiece.

01:36:38.977 --> 01:36:40.810
Of course, the eyepiece
is this whole thing.

01:36:40.810 --> 01:36:42.580
So that's where you
stick the eyepiece.

01:36:42.580 --> 01:36:43.460
So this is standard.

01:36:43.460 --> 01:36:46.370
In microscopes, it
is 160 millimeters

01:36:46.370 --> 01:36:48.100
and is known as the tube length.

01:36:48.100 --> 01:36:51.990
And this is what appears
in this formula over here.

01:36:51.990 --> 01:36:55.800
So basically, you can see that
if you pick the focal length

01:36:55.800 --> 01:36:58.050
to be sufficiently
small, then you

01:36:58.050 --> 01:37:01.590
can get very high magnification
in the order of hundreds, maybe

01:37:01.590 --> 01:37:06.640
even 1,000.

01:37:06.640 --> 01:37:08.720
Let me ask two questions now.

01:37:08.720 --> 01:37:15.710
First of all, what I just said.

01:37:15.710 --> 01:37:19.370
What do you think might stop
me from getting a focal length

01:37:19.370 --> 01:37:23.050
that is, let's say, 1 micron?

01:37:23.050 --> 01:37:25.650
I pick a focal length to be
1 micron, and then I have--

01:37:25.650 --> 01:37:27.350
these are all in millimeters.

01:37:27.350 --> 01:37:30.380
So 160 millimeters over 1
micron, that would be what?

01:37:30.380 --> 01:37:33.980
That would be about 160,000.

01:37:33.980 --> 01:37:36.920
And then another micron here,
I would get a magnification

01:37:36.920 --> 01:37:38.720
in the order of 1 billion.

01:37:38.720 --> 01:37:39.970
What stops me from doing that?

01:37:43.140 --> 01:37:44.570
First of all, just
to get back to,

01:37:44.570 --> 01:37:46.910
what is it from your experience?

01:37:46.910 --> 01:37:50.825
What is a typical magnification
that you get in microscopes?

01:37:50.825 --> 01:37:53.880
How about 1,000
orders of magnitude?

01:37:53.880 --> 01:37:56.060
But if you apply
this formula here,

01:37:56.060 --> 01:37:58.860
you could easily get a
magnification of 1 billion

01:37:58.860 --> 01:38:01.760
by picking the focal
length to be 1 micron.

01:38:01.760 --> 01:38:04.132
What is wrong with my statement?

01:38:04.132 --> 01:38:05.090
Clearly, there's wrong.

01:38:05.090 --> 01:38:07.605
Otherwise, people
would be doing it.

01:38:07.605 --> 01:38:09.740
AUDIENCE: Is it
because you can't see

01:38:09.740 --> 01:38:11.800
past the wave length of light?

01:38:11.800 --> 01:38:13.307
That 1 micron is
the most you could

01:38:13.307 --> 01:38:14.390
focus because that's the--

01:38:19.010 --> 01:38:21.170
PROFESSOR: That is in the
correct direction, yes.

01:38:28.410 --> 01:38:30.380
The other possible
reason is the failure

01:38:30.380 --> 01:38:32.320
of the paraxial approximation.

01:38:32.320 --> 01:38:36.810
But the paraxial approximation
may fail all at once.

01:38:36.810 --> 01:38:40.630
But I can always do something
more sophisticated to do

01:38:40.630 --> 01:38:42.848
non-paraxial calculations.

01:38:42.848 --> 01:38:45.390
Maybe you're saying that if the
paraxial approximation fails,

01:38:45.390 --> 01:38:47.750
then this formula fails as well.

01:38:47.750 --> 01:38:50.400
So then you don't get
as good magnification.

01:38:50.400 --> 01:38:53.740
I think you guys both
captured-- the two of you

01:38:53.740 --> 01:38:56.790
captured the answer in its
entirety You have another one?

01:38:56.790 --> 01:38:59.080
AUDIENCE: I don't
know if it's another.

01:38:59.080 --> 01:39:01.960
To make such a high--

01:39:01.960 --> 01:39:04.870
such a short focal
length lens we'll

01:39:04.870 --> 01:39:07.170
have to make a very big lens.

01:39:07.170 --> 01:39:08.690
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:39:08.690 --> 01:39:10.300
So you have to be
very highly curved.

01:39:10.300 --> 01:39:12.640
Remember the focal
length of the lens

01:39:12.640 --> 01:39:18.820
is proportional to the
radius of curvature.

01:39:18.820 --> 01:39:21.030
So you would have to
make a lens with a radius

01:39:21.030 --> 01:39:23.460
of curvature equal to 1 micron.

01:39:23.460 --> 01:39:26.140
And that's when you get
into problems like the--

01:39:26.140 --> 01:39:28.510
what's your name again?

01:39:28.510 --> 01:39:31.825
[INAUDIBLE] answered
the question before.

01:39:31.825 --> 01:39:32.980
AUDIENCE: Dean.

01:39:32.980 --> 01:39:33.920
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:39:33.920 --> 01:39:37.730
This is what Dean answered.

01:39:37.730 --> 01:39:43.360
If you try to make a curvature
that is as sharp as 1 micron,

01:39:43.360 --> 01:39:46.960
then basically you
get into the range

01:39:46.960 --> 01:39:49.413
of very strong
diffraction of light.

01:39:49.413 --> 01:39:50.830
So basically all
these geometrical

01:39:50.830 --> 01:39:52.390
optics that we do
here, they fail.

01:39:52.390 --> 01:39:55.870
In fact, you discover if you did
make such a very small element

01:39:55.870 --> 01:39:58.630
that the light does
not really focus.

01:39:58.630 --> 01:39:59.740
We'll see what it does.

01:39:59.740 --> 01:40:01.850
But it does not propagate.

01:40:01.850 --> 01:40:07.510
So reasonable focal lengths are
in the range of 1 centimeter,

01:40:07.510 --> 01:40:08.410
a few millimeters.

01:40:08.410 --> 01:40:11.660
These are typical microscope
objective focal length.

01:40:11.660 --> 01:40:12.910
And the eyepieces are similar.

01:40:12.910 --> 01:40:14.660
And that's why you
get magnification

01:40:14.660 --> 01:40:19.047
on the order of 1,000.

01:40:19.047 --> 01:40:20.380
The next topic is the telescope.

01:40:20.380 --> 01:40:24.220
But I think I've
exhausted your endurance.